To create a TikZ LaTeX diagram representing a symplectic billiard bounce \((p_1, p_3) \mapsto (p_2, p_3)\) in a strictly convex domain \(\Omega\), we need to visualize the domain, the initial point \(p_1\), the final point \(p_2\), and the trajectory of the ball.

Here is a sample TikZ code that accomplishes this:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2]
    % Define the vertices of the strictly convex domain
    \coordinate (A) at (-2, 0);
    \coordinate (B) at (0, 2);
    \coordinate (C) at (2, 0);
    \coordinate (D) at (0, -2);

    % Draw the boundary of the domain
    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;

    % Mark the initial point p1 and the final point p2
    \fill[red] (0, 0) circle (2pt) node[above right] {$p_1$};
    \fill[blue] (1, 1) circle (2pt) node[above left] {$p_2$};

    % Draw the trajectory from p1 to p2
    \draw[-stealth, thick, red] (0, 0) -- (1, 1);

    % Draw the reflection line at the boundary
    \draw[dashed, thick, blue] (0, 0) -- (1, -1);

    % Label the points on the boundary for clarity
    \node at (-2, 0.5) {$A$};
    \node at (0.5, 2) {$B$};
    \node at (2, 0.5) {$C$};
    \node at (0.5, -2) {$D$};

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

